  "why": "The paper provides diagnostic insight into where and how jailbreak failures occur through statistical and ablation analyses (e.g., ASR/EASR across models, transferability results, seed-selection and mutator ablations, and visualization of seed-tree exploration). These analyses characterize failure patterns and which fuzzer design choices lead to successful or diverse jailbreaks, but the paper does not trace failures to underlying model vulnerabilities such as corrupted/biased training data, reliance on spurious features, or internal model activations. Therefore it offers partial (pattern- and internals-adjacent) diagnostic understanding but not root-cause explanations tied to model internals or training data.",
  "evidence": "Pg. 11, Section 4.3 (Experiment III): “These templates displayed a notable degree of transferability. ... As depicted in Figure 4, when evaluated against Vicuna-13B, Baichuan-13B, ChatGLM-6B, Llama-2-13B/70B, Claude1, and PaLM2, the EASR for LLM-FUZZER consistently exceeded 80%...” ; Pg. 12, Table 2 and accompanying text (Experiment IV ablations): “No matter which replacements were implemented, they consistently led to a decrease in template effectiveness. This straightforwardly demonstrates that our design stands out as the most superior among all potential design options.” and the table shows ASR/EASR changes for different seed-selection and mutator variants; Pg. 6-7, Section 3.2 (Seed Selection): “To harness the advantages of effectiveness offered by MCTS and UCB while preserving diversity, we have introduced a specialized seed selection mechanism ... ‘MCTS-Explore’ ... This design encourages MCTS to balance its selection between deep and shallow nodes, thereby enhancing the diversity of selected seeds.”; Pg. 12, Section 5 (Discussion, Limitations): “The success of LLM-FUZZER partially relies on the oracle’s ability to accurately determine whether a response constitutes a jailbreak. We utilized a RoBERTa model as our oracle, and while it has proven effective, its accuracy is not 100% ... The potential for misclassification presents a challenge, as false positives or negatives could misguide the fuzzing process.”"
